    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>To Right the Wrongs of Slavery</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Kelly Sarabyn letter endorses Glenn C Loury's May 29 Op-Ed article opposing payment of reparations to the descendants of slaves</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''It's Futile to Put a Price on Slavery'' (Op-Ed, May 29), arguing against reparations for slavery:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''It's Futile to Put a Price on Slavery'' (Op-Ed, May 29), arguing against reparations for slavery:</p>
        <p>Taking money from citizens to redress their ancestors' behavior is rooted in the same immorality as slavery: punishing someone for something out of his control. I cannot change my forefathers' behavior any more than my skin color, so why should I be penalized for either?</p>
        <p>Tort law requires an injured party and an offender, and in the case of slavery, both parties are dead. Why should we reimburse an African-American born into poverty and offer nothing to a white person born into poverty?</p>
        <p>KELLY SARABYN  Centreville, Va., May 29, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
